definition.value: An Italian pasta sauce from Rome made with egg, hard cheese, guanciale (or pancetta), and black pepper.

A northern Italian rice dish cooked with broth until it reaches a creamy consistency. The broth can be derived from meat, fish, or vegetables. Many types of risotto contain butter, onion, white wine, and parmesan cheese.

A French Provençal stewed vegetable dish, originating in Nice, and sometimes referred to as ratatouille niçoise. Recipes and cooking times differ widely, but common ingredients include tomato, garlic, onion, zucchini, aubergine (eggplant), bell pepper, and some combination of leafy green herbs common to the region.
A dish from Savoy in the Alps. It is made with potatoes, reblochon cheese, lardons and onions.
A Maghrebi dish which is named after the earthenware pot in which it is cooked.

A Levantine vegetarian salad made mostly of finely chopped parsley, with tomatoes, mint, onion, bulgur (soaked, not cooked), and seasoned with olive oil, lemon juice, salt and pepper. Some variations add garlic or lettuce, or use couscous instead of bulgur.
A Japanese dish of prepared vinegared rice, usually with some sugar and salt, accompanying a variety of ingredients, such as seafood, vegetables, and occasionally tropical fruits.

A baked egg-based dish which originated in early eighteenth-century France. It is made with egg yolks and beaten egg whites combined with various other ingredients and served as a savory main dish or sweetened as a dessert.
A mixture of creamed fish or meat, sometimes combined with breadcrumbs, with a light egg binding, formed into an egg-like shape, and then cooked, usually by poaching.
An Italian dry-cured ham that is usually thinly sliced and served uncooked.

A sandwich traditionally made with Italian bread (such as ciabatta, and michetta), usually served warmed by grilling or toasting.  In many English-speaking countries other types of bread such as baguettes may be used.
A salumi made of pork belly meat that is salt cured.
A Spanish rice dish originally from Valencia, named after the wide, shallow traditional pan used to cook the dish.
A castrated adult cattle male (occasionally a female or in some areas a bull) kept for draft or riding purposes.
Ox as a prefix may also be used to refer to some carcass products from any adult cattle, such as ox-hide, ox-blood, oxtail, or ox-liver. [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cattle#Terminology]

A dish made from beaten eggs fried with butter or oil in a frying pan (without stirring as in scrambled egg). It is quite common for the omelette to be folded around fillings such as cheese, chives, vegetables, mushrooms, meat (often ham or bacon), or some combination of the above.
An eggplant- (aubergine) or potato-based dish, often including ground meat, in the Levant, Middle East, and Balkans, with many local and regional variations.

A French pastry traditionally made up of three layers of puff pastry (pâte feuilletée), alternating with two layers of pastry cream (crème pâtissière). The top pastry layer is dusted with confectioner's sugar, and sometimes cocoa, pastry crumbs, or pulverized seeds (e.g. roasted almonds) or is glazed with icing or fondant in alternating white (icing) and brown (chocolate) stripes, and combed.

An Italian cream cheese recognized as a Prodotto agroalimentare tradizionale (traditional regional food product), it is coagulated by the addition of certain acidic substances such as lemon juice, vinegar or citric acid.
A top-fermented beer made with predominantly pale malt.
A hoppy beer style within the broader category of pale ale.

Yogurt that has been strained to remove most of its whey, resulting in a thicker consistency than unstrained yogurt, while preserving yogurt's distinctive sour taste. Like many types of yogurt, strained yogurt is often made from milk that has been enriched by boiling off some of its water content, or by adding extra butterfat and powdered milk. In Europe and North America, it is often made from low-fat or fat-free milk.
A sauce made from a white roux (butter and flour) and milk.

A dish originating from the Indian subcontinent, consisting of chicken stewed in an onion- and tomato-based sauce, flavoured with curry powder and or ginger, garlic, tomato puree, chilli peppers, turmeric, cumin, coriander, cinnamon, cardamom etc.
A dish of ground meat covered with mashed potatoes and baked, similar to the British dish shepherd's pie.
A meat pie with a crust or topping of mashed potato.
A regional dish of Savoyard gastronomy based on processed cheese and bread. It is prepared from cheesaes such as the mountain county , Beaufort , Gruyère de Savoie , Emmental of Savoy.
A dish of beef dipped in fondue, originating in Switzerland.
Fat (in the strict sense) specifically refers to lipids that are solids at room temperature.
A fruit multiple of a fig plant (Ficus carica).
An additive used to modify flavour
A tartiflette except that small squares of pasta, crozets de Savoie (usually made from buckwheat but sometimes durum) are used instead of potatoes.
A baked or fried boiled ham and cheese sandwich.

A cut of pork popular in Western and Asian cuisines. The ribcage of a domestic pig, meat and bones together, is cut into usable pieces, prepared by smoking, grilling, or baking – usually with a sauce, often barbecue – and then served.

A Tex-Mex and Mexican cuisine dish usually served as a taco on a flour or corn tortilla, with toppings including cooked skirt steak or other cuts of beef, chicken, as well as vegetables instead of meat.  In restaurants, the meat is usually cooked with onions and bell peppers.
A dish of meat wrapped around cheese (or with cheese filling), then breaded and pan-fried or deep-fried.
A type of pasta made with fresh eggs and found in the cuisines of southern Germany and Austria, Switzerland, Hungary, Slovenia, Alsace, Moselle and South Tyrol.
A prepared coffee beverage without cream or sugar.
A coffee-flavoured Italian dessert made of ladyfingers (savoiardi) dipped in coffee, layered with a whipped mixture of eggs, sugar, and mascarpone cheese, flavoured with cocoa.

Red velvet cake is traditionally a red, red-brown, crimson or scarlet colored chocolate layer cake, layered with white cream cheese or ermine icing. Traditional recipes do not use food coloring, with the red color due to non-Dutched, anthocyanin-rich cocoa.
Steeped tea made from dried Rooibos plant (Aspalathus linearis) tea leaves.

A dish originating in Switzerland and prepared from raclette cheese round which is heated, either in front of a fire or by a special machine, then scraped onto diners' plates. It is accompanied by small firm potatoes, cornichons, pickled onions, and dried meat.
A tart French pickle made from a small gherkin pickled in vinegar and tarragon.
A soup product in liquid form.

A fisheries term for several species of demersal fish with fins, particularly Atlantic cod (Gadus morhua), whiting (Merluccius bilinearis), haddock (Melanogrammus aeglefinus), hake (Urophycis), pollock (Pollachius), and others.
A sexually mature female bird.
A food ingredient that is prepared by scraping or cutting from the outer, colorful skin of unwaxed citrus fruits such as lemon, orange, citron, and lime. Zest is used to add flavor to foods.
